ğŸ§  Core Logic (Explain BEFORE Code)

â€œFirst, I count the frequency of each character.
Then, I traverse the string again in the same order and return the first character whose frequency is 1.â€

ğŸ“Œ Why 2 loops?

HashMap doesnâ€™t preserve original order

String order matters for â€œfirstâ€ 


import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s = "swiss";
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        // Step 1: Count frequency
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(c, map.getOrDefault(c, 0) + 1);
        }

        // Step 2: Find first non-repeating character
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (map.get(c) == 1) {
                System.out.println(c);
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}



Time Complexity: O(n)

1 loop for counting

1 loop for checking

Space Complexity: O(n)

HashMap stores characters

ğŸ¤ How to Explain This in Interview (Exact Lines)

â€œI use HashMap to store frequency of characters.
Then I traverse the string again to preserve order and find the first character whose frequency is one.
This approach runs in linear time.â€
 
